01:00:58.348 --> 01:01:01.408
related to relation with POSN1 and melanoma cells,

1018
01:01:02.288 --> 01:01:06.068
we just received some results about the

1019
01:01:06.148 --> 01:01:09.268
RNA sequencing of melanoma cells similar to

1020
01:01:09.848 --> 01:01:13.768
recombinant POSN1. So maybe at the next meeting, I could give you more

1021
01:01:13.808 --> 01:01:16.028
answer about the relation. But yeah.

1022
01:01:16.348 --> 01:01:16.888
Thank you.

1023
01:01:16.948 --> 01:01:17.208
Thank you.

1024
01:01:19.156 --> 01:01:23.036
Hi. I just wanted to comment on your experiment specifically

1025
01:01:23.076 --> 01:01:26.816
with the geriatric mice, where you depleted the gamma delta T

1026
01:01:26.896 --> 01:01:30.556
cells. I was wondering if you were considering doing another study on the younger

1027
01:01:30.616 --> 01:01:34.056
mice, which showed some similarities to the geriatric mice, and maybe

1028
01:01:34.356 --> 01:01:37.356
thinking of depleting the gamma T cells in that and seeing how that might-

1029
01:01:38.396 --> 01:01:40.936
You mean to do the same experiment but apply to young mice?

1030
01:01:41.616 --> 01:01:41.706
Yes.

1031
01:01:41.706 --> 01:01:44.116
Yeah. So I done this experiment

1032
01:01:45.216 --> 01:01:49.056
first, but I would like to repeat it

1033
01:01:49.416 --> 01:01:51.376
with a different melanoma cell type.

1034
01:01:52.236 --> 01:01:56.216
Because I've done it in first with just healthy condition to see

1035
01:01:56.836 --> 01:02:00.696
how the depletion of gamma delta T cell will

1036
01:02:00.756 --> 01:02:03.956
involve a dysregulation in young or aged microenvironments.

1037
01:02:04.316 --> 01:02:08.086
And I just need to do it with the injection of melanoma

1038
01:02:08.176 --> 01:02:09.456
cells. Thank you.

1039
01:02:11.756 --> 01:02:12.616
Thank you very much.

1040
01:02:13.066 --> 01:02:13.066
Thank you.

1041
01:02:13.096 --> 01:02:13.706
Oh, sorry.

1042
01:02:13.756 --> 01:02:14.096
There is an-

1043
01:02:14.196 --> 01:02:15.296
The lights were blinding.

1044
01:02:16.676 --> 01:02:17.116
Leave the light.

1045
01:02:17.976 --> 01:02:20.156
Hi. My name is Ajinkya. I'm from Mass General.

1046
01:02:21.916 --> 01:02:22.896
Great talk, by the way.

1047
01:02:23.056 --> 01:02:23.336
Thank you.

1048
01:02:23.395 --> 01:02:26.016
Quick question related to myeloid-derived suppressor cells.

1049
01:02:26.396 --> 01:02:30.266
By any chance, have you seen them, like senescent myeloid-derived suppressor

1050
01:02:30.296 --> 01:02:33.416
cells causing the inhibition of your gamma delta T cells?

1051
01:02:34.176 --> 01:02:38.086
And would you use the senolytics to clear them off and

1052
01:02:38.176 --> 01:02:40.476
see if the population rises?

1053
01:02:40.516 --> 01:02:41.996
So we haven't directly

1054
01:02:44.016 --> 01:02:47.936
look at the interaction between MDSC cells and gamma delta

1055
01:02:47.976 --> 01:02:51.776
T cells. It's something we would like to

1056
01:02:51.846 --> 01:02:52.516
do later,

1057
01:02:53.336 --> 01:02:57.216
because we need to isolate MDSC cells and do

1058
01:02:57.256 --> 01:03:01.026
co-culture with gamma delta T cells to look at what impact it could have.

1059
01:03:01.086 --> 01:03:03.476
But yeah, it's something we would like to do later. Thank you.

1060
01:03:05.676 --> 01:03:06.906
Okay. Now, thank you very much.

1061
01:03:06.956 --> 01:03:07.536
Thank you.

1062
01:03:07.576 --> 01:03:08.136
Thank you.

1063
01:03:11.276 --> 01:03:13.636
All right. Our next speaker is M Spacek.

1064
01:03:14.416 --> 01:03:17.986
The title of the talk is Age Stratified Therapeutic Strategies

1065
01:03:18.696 --> 01:03:22.616
Targeting Tumor Cell Subclones That Drive Chemoresistance and Immunosuppression

1066
01:03:22.656 --> 01:03:24.396
in Triple Negative Breast Cancer.

1067
01:03:30.876 --> 01:03:32.535
Hi, everyone. Thank you for coming today.

1068
01:03:33.026 --> 01:03:36.726
I'm going to be talking about how aging impacts triple negative breast cancer,

1069
01:03:37.136 --> 01:03:40.856
disease progression, and therapeutic responses, and then also how we were able to

1070
01:03:40.956 --> 01:03:44.056
use a new DNA barcoding system to

1071
01:03:44.116 --> 01:03:47.676
identify a subset of cells within these tumors that is resistant to

1072
01:03:47.716 --> 01:03:51.616
chemotherapy, that we're then able to target to try to improve

1073
01:03:51.676 --> 01:03:53.136
outcomes with age.

1074
01:03:55.196 --> 01:03:58.616
So this has already been discussed numerous times, but age is the biggest risk

1075
01:03:58.636 --> 01:04:01.456
factor for developing most forms of cancer.

1076
01:04:01.496 --> 01:04:05.376
To the effect that over 60% of new cancer cases each year are in

1077
01:04:05.416 --> 01:04:08.766
patients over 65 years old. The problem, however, is

1078
01:04:08.816 --> 01:04:12.636
that less than 25% of patients that are enrolled in clinical trials are in that

1079
01:04:12.676 --> 01:04:16.536
age range. This is also compounded by the fact that the majority of

1080
01:04:16.576 --> 01:04:20.476
preclinical models are performed in young animals, meaning that

1081
01:04:20.556 --> 01:04:24.336
from the preclinical through clinical stages, we're not accurately reflecting the

1082
01:04:24.356 --> 01:04:28.316
patient populations most suffering from these conditions, as almost everyone else

1083
01:04:28.356 --> 01:04:29.556
here today has been talking about.

1084
01:04:31.096 --> 01:04:35.046
And in the case of triple negative breast cancer, we have seen that

1085
01:04:35.076 --> 01:04:37.956
this is actually a molecularly distinct disease with age.

1086
01:04:38.456 --> 01:04:41.576
We've looked at a number of different data sets, but one example is looking at the

1087
01:04:41.636 --> 01:04:45.156
Metabric data set and stratifying patients by under 40 versus over

1088
01:04:45.356 --> 01:04:49.285
65. We see that there's a lot of differentially expressed genes, and a lot

1089
01:04:49.336 --> 01:04:51.845
of these programs are related to immune responses.

1090
01:04:52.396 --> 01:04:56.316
Which also makes sense because with age, it's also very well known

1091
01:04:56.356 --> 01:04:57.776
that immune function changes.

1092
01:04:59.436 --> 01:05:03.166
We also recently published a single cell analysis also confirming

1093
01:05:03.176 --> 01:05:05.196
these results at the single cell level.

1094
01:05:05.296 --> 01:05:08.236
So I encourage anyone to dig through that data set as well.

1095
01:05:08.256 --> 01:05:12.096
We also found striking differences between triple negative versus hormone

1096
01:05:12.136 --> 01:05:13.336
receptor positive disease.

1097
01:05:15.746 --> 01:05:18.776
Specifically with the case of triple negative breast cancer, we know that this is a

1098
01:05:18.856 --> 01:05:22.716
very highly aggressive disease. It's the most aggressive subtype of breast

1099
01:05:22.736 --> 01:05:23.076
cancer,

1100
01:05:23.996 --> 01:05:25.736
and it lacks any targeted therapies.

1101
01:05:25.876 --> 01:05:29.096
Meaning that the standard of care now is typically a combination of

1102
01:05:29.116 --> 01:05:31.065
chemotherapy with an immunotherapy.

1103
01:05:31.916 --> 01:05:35.506
However, these treatments often lead to resistance,

1104
01:05:35.616 --> 01:05:38.466
particularly to chemotherapy in the older population.

1105
01:05:39.066 --> 01:05:42.796
And also the older populations don't tolerate chemotherapy quite as

1106
01:05:42.836 --> 01:05:46.376
well. So we think that we need to start, one, identifying new age

1107
01:05:46.436 --> 01:05:50.276
stratified treatment strategies to better treat patients of all ages,

1108
01:05:50.956 --> 01:05:54.836
but also attempt to remove toxic chemotherapy from patients that don't

1109
01:05:54.896 --> 01:05:55.716
tolerate it as well.

1110
01:05:58.256 --> 01:06:02.216
So to start to pre-clinically analyze this and dig into the

1111
01:06:02.256 --> 01:06:06.216
role of aging and triple negative breast cancer, we're using the FVB

1112
01:06:06.276 --> 01:06:09.136
strain of mice. So this is a fully immunocompetent strain of mice,

1113
01:06:10.056 --> 01:06:13.576
and we start with them around eight to 10 weeks old, as our young cohort.

1114
01:06:13.616 --> 01:06:17.336
And then we also age mice in-house until they're around 14 months old.

1115
01:06:17.896 --> 01:06:21.786
And we have profiled the peripheral blood of these mice at these ages

1116
01:06:21.816 --> 01:06:25.266
from cancer-free mice, and we see that they have an expansion of neutrophils,

1117
01:06:25.356 --> 01:06:29.276
shifting from lymphocyte to monocyte populations, reductions in different

1118
01:06:29.316 --> 01:06:33.256
T cell subsets within the blood, all hallmarks of healthy

1119
01:06:33.276 --> 01:06:36.716
immune aging. And so we think that our model accurately reflects

1120
01:06:37.056 --> 01:06:39.896
patients that are over 60 years old in this older cohort.

1121
01:06:41.056 --> 01:06:44.676
But importantly also, this strain of mice does start to develop

1122
01:06:44.756 --> 01:06:46.326
some comorbidities after

1123
01:06:47.316 --> 01:06:51.116
one year, year and a half old. And so at this time point, our mice

1124
01:06:51.156 --> 01:06:54.296
don't exhibit noticeable other comorbidities.

1125
01:06:54.336 --> 01:06:58.096
So we think that most of the responses that we see are due to immune aging.

1126
01:07:00.736 --> 01:07:04.576
And so we then took these mice and injected them with

1127
01:07:04.676 --> 01:07:07.096
syngeneic Met1 triple negative breast cancer cells.

1128
01:07:07.916 --> 01:07:11.856
And then we treated the mice with either paclitaxel chemotherapy

1129
01:07:12.016 --> 01:07:14.776
or combination with anti-PD-L1 immunotherapy.

1130
01:07:15.816 --> 01:07:19.216
And what we see immediately, and we've published on this before, is

1131
01:07:19.236 --> 01:07:23.156
thatThe tumor growth is much more aggressive in the younger

1132
01:07:23.216 --> 01:07:26.816
mice, so the disease is just more aggressive in younger.

1133
01:07:27.556 --> 01:07:30.986
But you can see that when we apply monotherapy and combination therapy,

1134
01:07:31.716 --> 01:07:35.316
the young mice really get a nice stratification of responses to treatment, where

1135
01:07:35.356 --> 01:07:38.726
the combination therapy really outperforms either monotherapy.

1136
01:07:39.756 --> 01:07:42.836
But in the aged mice on the right, they respond a little bit to treatment, but they

1137
01:07:42.896 --> 01:07:46.596
don't get any additional benefit of combination therapy over monotherapy.

1138
01:07:47.716 --> 01:07:51.636
And if we plot the change in tumor volume from these treatments relative to the

1139
01:07:51.656 --> 01:07:52.636
age-matched control,

1140
01:07:53.476 --> 01:07:57.205
we see that the young mice really get a robust response to treatment,

1141
01:07:57.436 --> 01:08:01.136
and particularly, a significant benefit of combination therapy

1142
01:08:01.256 --> 01:08:05.096
over monotherapy alone. However, the older mice on the far right

1143
01:08:06.376 --> 01:08:09.796
do not have any significant benefit of combination over monotherapy.

1144
01:08:09.836 --> 01:08:12.775
And they just overall don't respond nearly as well to treatments.

1145
01:08:13.256 --> 01:08:16.696
So again, highlighting that with these older mice, we potentially need alternative

1146
01:08:16.776 --> 01:08:20.436
treatment strategies and maybe ones that don't rely on chemotherapy.

1147
01:08:22.316 --> 01:08:25.226
So we next wanted to molecularly understand a little bit what was going on here,

1148
01:08:25.246 --> 01:08:28.876
and so we performed bulk RNA sequencing on those same tumors and then performed

1149
01:08:28.896 --> 01:08:32.736
gene set enrichment analysis for hallmark pathways here, where everything here

1150
01:08:33.036 --> 01:08:36.757
in red is significantly enriched in a treatment versus its

1151
01:08:36.837 --> 01:08:37.717
age-matched control.

1152
01:08:38.757 --> 01:08:42.637
And in the young mice, we see that there's a lot of those immune response

1153
01:08:42.717 --> 01:08:45.196
programs are enriched with treatment.

1154
01:08:46.436 --> 01:08:49.896
And that potentially explains then why the younger mice were able to have a more

1155
01:08:49.936 --> 01:08:53.916
robust response to treatment. However, the older mice, you can see on

1156
01:08:53.956 --> 01:08:55.976
the right here, don't have nearly as

1157
01:08:56.856 --> 01:09:00.476
robust of a molecular reprogramming and molecular response

1158
01:09:01.056 --> 01:09:04.587
as the younger mice do to treatment, and particularly the paclitaxel group that

1159
01:09:04.637 --> 01:09:08.496
I've highlighted here in green has almost no molecular change.

1160
01:09:08.576 --> 01:09:12.257
And these are only some of the pathways that we've seen, but it's almost as if

1161
01:09:12.396 --> 01:09:16.337
the paclitaxel just is not really doing as much in these older mice.

1162
01:09:17.177 --> 01:09:20.416
Again, adding to the fact that we need alternatives to

1163
01:09:20.736 --> 01:09:21.356
paclitaxel.

1164
01:09:23.257 --> 01:09:27.156
So another aspect of this study is that all of the cells that I used

1165
01:09:27.396 --> 01:09:30.885
in this preclinical model contain DNA barcodes.

1166
01:09:31.076 --> 01:09:34.996
So, I will only summarize this briefly, this method, and

1167
01:09:35.016 --> 01:09:38.637
you can check out our paper if you want to see more details of how we do this.

1168
01:09:38.656 --> 01:09:41.797
But in short, we single-cell clone

1169
01:09:42.637 --> 01:09:46.337
heterogeneous population and isolate single-cell clones and

1170
01:09:47.996 --> 01:09:51.856
preserve them independently. And then we infect each of those with its own

1171
01:09:51.916 --> 01:09:54.306
unique DNA barcode. So that way we have

1172
01:09:55.376 --> 01:09:59.276
here, in this case, we have 31 clones of sub-cloned cells that each

1173
01:09:59.316 --> 01:10:00.556
have their own unique DNA barcode.

1174
01:10:00.586 --> 01:10:03.616
So we can track them longitudinally in vivo, in vitro.

1175
01:10:03.756 --> 01:10:04.816
We can also

1176
01:10:05.776 --> 01:10:08.446
profile those cells against each other to see molecularly

1177
01:10:08.476 --> 01:10:12.306
at the protein level how they might be distinct from each other.

1178
01:10:12.316 --> 01:10:16.096
We can also, though, take these cells and recombine them in any way that we want to

1179
01:10:16.136 --> 01:10:17.176
make custom tumors.

1180
01:10:18.496 --> 01:10:21.336
And all of this is detectable by qPCR.

1181
01:10:23.036 --> 01:10:27.016
So we found with this that when we treat either young or aged mice with

1182
01:10:27.056 --> 01:10:30.896
paclitaxel, there's only one clone that significantly increases after

1183
01:10:30.946 --> 01:10:31.976
paclitaxel treatment.

1184
01:10:32.856 --> 01:10:36.176
And we call it barcode 25, but the name doesn't really matter.

1185
01:10:36.816 --> 01:10:40.716
But it increases in both young and aged mice with chemotherapy treatment.

1186
01:10:41.736 --> 01:10:45.705
And when we implant these cells as a clonal tumor into mice and

1187
01:10:45.736 --> 01:10:49.386
then treat with paclitaxel, they still maintain complete resistance to

1188
01:10:49.416 --> 01:10:50.076
paclitaxel.

1189
01:10:52.756 --> 01:10:53.276
So we then

1190
01:10:54.456 --> 01:10:58.176
took these cells and mixed them, and I generated a couple of custom

1191
01:10:58.256 --> 01:11:01.426
pools that either contained the most dominant clones within the tumors,

1192
01:11:02.436 --> 01:11:05.596
plus or minus that chemo-resistant clone, which is in the blue bars.

1193
01:11:06.596 --> 01:11:10.136
And when we do this, we see that even a small amount of this clone, and actually in

1194
01:11:10.176 --> 01:11:12.716
these tumors, it only takes up less than 5% of the tumor,

1195
01:11:13.796 --> 01:11:17.596
it drives an increase in PD-L1 expression, in interferon gamma expression,

1196
01:11:18.556 --> 01:11:22.236
the immune recruitment factor CXCL10, but it also increases

1197
01:11:22.336 --> 01:11:26.236
EMT factors such as vimentin and immunosuppression factors such as

1198
01:11:26.316 --> 01:11:26.836
Ebi3.

1199
01:11:28.876 --> 01:11:32.396
So we took these chemo-resistant cells, and then we wanted to see if we could

1200
01:11:32.436 --> 01:11:33.356
actually target them

1201
01:11:34.376 --> 01:11:38.066
therapeutically. And so we did a drug screen using an FDA-approved

1202
01:11:38.136 --> 01:11:38.955
compound library,

1203
01:11:40.096 --> 01:11:43.976
and we actually found that the top hits, most of the top hits were

1204
01:11:44.036 --> 01:11:47.816
all pan-HDAC inhibitors or histone deacetylase inhibitors, with the

1205
01:11:47.876 --> 01:11:49.836
top hit in this screen being panobinostat.

1206
01:11:50.936 --> 01:11:51.176
So

1207
01:11:51.996 --> 01:11:55.636
we then just wanted to jump right to the end and see if we combine

1208
01:11:55.646 --> 01:11:59.586
this HDAC inhibitor with an immunotherapy, how does that

1209
01:11:59.616 --> 01:12:00.736
perform with age?

1210
01:12:01.976 --> 01:12:05.846
And we actually strikingly see that the combination of panobinostat and

1211
01:12:05.846 --> 01:12:08.976
anti-PD-L1, particularly in the aged mice, has a

1212
01:12:09.016 --> 01:12:12.816
significant benefit on increasing lifespan of these mice in that

1213
01:12:12.836 --> 01:12:16.376
pink line. Whereas the young mice on combination treatment are in the green

1214
01:12:16.416 --> 01:12:19.986
line. They still get a benefit over monotherapy,

1215
01:12:21.276 --> 01:12:23.656
but it's not nearly as striking as in those older mice.

1216
01:12:25.416 --> 01:12:28.996
However, young mice, since they still can tolerate the chemotherapy a little bit

1217
01:12:29.016 --> 01:12:30.296
better than the older mice,

1218
01:12:31.376 --> 01:12:34.876
we then did take some of these animals, and only in the young mice,

1219
01:12:35.216 --> 01:12:39.116
performed a triple combination with anti-PD-L1, panobinostat, and paclitaxel,

1220
01:12:39.756 --> 01:12:43.476
and we get almost complete tumor control with this triple

1221
01:12:43.556 --> 01:12:44.456
combination regimen.

1222
01:12:46.496 --> 01:12:50.446
And so just to quickly summarize all the data here, we know that age is the biggest

1223
01:12:50.476 --> 01:12:54.006
risk factor for developing most forms of cancer, including breast cancer,

1224
01:12:54.916 --> 01:12:58.306
but the toxic chemotherapy is really not that well-tolerated by the older patients.

1225
01:12:58.536 --> 01:13:02.376
But with this DNA barcoding system, we can identify a chemo-resistant population

1226
01:13:02.396 --> 01:13:02.936
and target it.

1227
01:13:04.016 --> 01:13:07.946
So we think that maybe HDAC inhibition could be a potential modality from

1228
01:13:07.996 --> 01:13:11.136
which we can build age-stratified treatment options in the future.

1229
01:13:12.516 --> 01:13:15.946
This comes with a little bit of a caveat, though, in that HDAC inhibitors,

1230
01:13:16.156 --> 01:13:19.776
pan-HDAC inhibitors, have been tested as monotherapies,

1231
01:13:20.156 --> 01:13:23.984
but they are met with some clinical toxicities.However, we think that

1232
01:13:24.384 --> 01:13:27.564
combination therapies may be able to lower those toxicities.

1233
01:13:28.224 --> 01:13:31.744
And as has been mentioned in several other sessions throughout the conference this

1234
01:13:31.804 --> 01:13:35.564
year, there are now starting to become some next-generation selective

1235
01:13:35.764 --> 01:13:39.644
HDAC inhibitors that could potentially further lower toxicities.

1236
01:13:41.724 --> 01:13:45.664
So with that, I'll acknowledge a whole host of people that made all of

1237
01:13:45.704 --> 01:13:49.004
this work possible, and I'll take any questions.

1238
01:13:55.424 --> 01:13:55.804
Okay.

1239
01:13:57.284 --> 01:14:00.844
If any questions for Milos, please come up to the microphones. I'll start.

1240
01:14:00.924 --> 01:14:02.964
I guess I have a question. Very nice talk.

1241
01:14:04.804 --> 01:14:07.884
And I'm wondering, so for other disease models that

1242
01:14:10.064 --> 01:14:13.304
take age into

1243
01:14:13.324 --> 01:14:17.034
consideration because the patients are mainly in the older

1244
01:14:17.044 --> 01:14:19.864
populations, I'm wondering about what you're finding.

1245
01:14:20.064 --> 01:14:23.894
Do you think any of it could be transferable to other cancer types?

1246
01:14:25.244 --> 01:14:29.094
So it's actually very tricky, but almost exciting because we've

1247
01:14:29.124 --> 01:14:32.844
seen very different responses with aging in different

1248
01:14:32.904 --> 01:14:36.644
cancer types. So melanomas respond much better with age to

1249
01:14:36.684 --> 01:14:40.564
immunotherapies. We do have some colleagues also that have looked at

1250
01:14:40.604 --> 01:14:44.144
HER2-positive disease, and it almost responds a little bit opposite

1251
01:14:44.264 --> 01:14:45.884
of triple-negative breast cancer.

1252
01:14:45.944 --> 01:14:48.284
So there's definitely

1253
01:14:49.024 --> 01:14:52.724
context-specific differences in how age impacts

